	   <tr><td colspan=2>Sorry man, but the real enchanters learn over their lives how to manage aggro and how to let the group take a few more hits of damage if it means you having more chances to mez without getting killed.&nbsp;&nbsp;One of the worst mistakes I see channers make is to "hurry up" and throw all their spells on a mob as fast as they can as they come in.  The revamp to Tash making it less aggro was a huge improvement... but even now if I were ever foolish enough to tash right away and follow right up with a slow, I can almost guarantee the mob will break off to hit me even with a 55+ warrior taunting.  Sometimes this is desireable (I want to get my pet hitting on the mob) but most of the time your best form of AC is not geting aggroed in the first place.  My AC is crap, but I'll live through 99% of all encounters becasue I've learned when to apply tash, when to mem blur becasue I've built up too much aggro, etc.  Instead my cha, int, and mana are pushed out to the max (more stress on cha) so that I can mez most things first bang and *not* have to be in a position where I'm hoping I can channel a recast through.<br><br>Oh and it's Channeling... that helps you regain concentration.  If everything is relative, take a level 25, 35, 45, 55 enchanter, each as maxed out as they can be in channeling, but each with exactly 250 agility, and I can guarantee the level 55 will channel more spells through being hit than any of them.  AGI helps you dodge, sure, but it's your channeling skill that will let you land a cast through a quadhit of 150 ;)<br>&nbsp;<br>Lasombra Corazon<br>Illumin Cathari, Solusek Ro<br></td></tr>
